The HSP of the materials was evaluated by using thirty-five solvents with distinct HSP values [30,31] (see Table S1). Briefly, for each glass vial containing 3 mL of solvent, 10 mg of the film was added. The tube was sealed with a suitable plug to prevent solvent evaporation. The films (WPU0 and WPU1) were then kept in the solvent for 20 days at 45 °C. A visual analysis categorized the behavior of the films in solution. The solvent was considered incompatible or insoluble if the film remained intact after this period (value = 0). If the film remained intact after this period, the solvent was considered incompatible or insoluble (value = 0). Solvents in which the films were well dissolved after 20 days were classified as soluble or compatible (value = 1). The HSP was estimated by fitting the dispersion data through the algorithm described by Gharagheizi [31]. This procedure fits the dispersion data to a sphere with the center defined by the dispersive (δ
                              D
                           ), polar (δ
                              P
                           ), and hydrogen bond (δ
                              H
                           ) interactions of the films. This sphere has a radius R

                              0
                            indicative of the maximum solution tolerance for which suitable solvents are located inside it while unsuitable ones are outside the sphere [30].

The incorporation of CQDs into the WPU did not promote a significant change in both the molecular weight (M

                           n
                        ) and the weight average molecular weight (M

                           w
                        ), as well as in the polydispersion index (M

                           w
                        /M

                           n
                        ). Considering that the aqueous solutions contain large amounts of CQDs and these are added to the prepolymer during the phase inversion step (T = 45 °C), it is believed that these CQDs can react with the –NCO groups due to the reaction being faster between with –NH2 groups [38]. This effect could result in a more significant hindrance to chain growth. The film's solubility behavior corroborates this result since no gel formation was observed for the samples containing 1.0 wt% CQDs. It is predicted that the polymerization between isocyanate and the surface functional groups present on CQDs will occur faster than its reaction with water since the reactivity between –NCO and amino groups (–NH2) is 1000 times faster than between –NCO and H2O or primary hydroxyl group. Furthermore, the reaction between –NCO and –NH2 is thermodynamically favorable at room temperature and does not need to be catalyzed [29,39]. The reaction between prepolymer –NCO end groups and humidity leads to the formation of carbamic acid, which is unstable and decomposes into carbon dioxide and amine. However, this reaction is extremely slow at low temperatures, requiring >18 days for the total conversion of the isocyanate groups [29]. The reaction model between –NCO groups and CQDs was evaluated by FTIR and is presented in the Supplementary material (Fig. S2).

DSC and TGA techniques investigated the thermal behavior of nanocomposites. From the DSC results (Fig. 2
                        ), two thermal events could be distinguished: a glass transition phenomenon close to −36 °C, associated with the flexible segments (T

                           gSS
                        ) (amorphous part), and a glass transition temperature close to 54 °C, possibly related to the rigid segments (T

                           gHS
                        ) [41,42]. Incorporating CQDs in the polymeric matrix discreetly influenced the value of T

                           gSS
                        . However, T

                           gHS
                         was shifted to higher temperatures by the addition of nanoparticles, which may have reduced the chain mobility in phase transition regions [43]. These results are in agreement with those already observed by FTIR. The thermograms in Fig. 2 were presented up to 100 °C, as no thermal event was detected above this temperature.

In addition, the thermal stability of the film with the best physical-mechanical properties was evaluated using TG and DTG. The thermal degradation temperature corresponding to 5 wt% mass loss (T

                           5%
                        ) increased from 252 °C to 270 °C with the incorporation of 1.0 wt% CQDs to the WPU [Fig. 3(a)]. The specific interactions between WPU and CQDs, such as covalent, hydrogen, and polar bondings, restrict the macromolecular chain mobility and may convert its linear structure to a rigid crosslinked network [16,20]. The bond-breaking process in the nanocomposites may require more heat since the specific WPU-CQDs interactions can hinder the diffusion of degradation products. The nanocomposites exhibited three stages of thermal decomposition: the first corresponds to the decomposition of the urethane bonds of the rigid segment; the second is associated with the decomposition of the flexible segment and other products resulting from the first stage, and the third, is related to the consumption of the carbonic portion of the polymer chain, leaving only CQDs trace.
